I was really looking forward to the food after seeing photos online and reading reviews however I have to say that the food was mediocre at best. We had a couple of entrees - octopus and tuna ceviche and then mains - burger. The flavors were nothing to write home about. After getting through the entrees we looked at each other and said: “is this really the 3rd best restaurant in Chicago?!”.  We have eaten at restaurants around the world - London, Paris, Cape Town, Sydney, Rome, etc. The food at this restaurant was just ok and certainly not deserving of 5 stars!

I generally don’t eat meat, but both the calamari and octopus were cooked to perfection, the avocado on toast also had a nice twist to it. I’ve never been able to find these items on the menu, so maybe we got lucky! But based on how the food we were so generously given tasted, I’d go back to Tzuco anytime!

This review will not be enough to share just how AMAZING Tzuco is. Celebrated a friends birthday here and it was the perfect place! You feel “special” from the moment you walk in. We went during the end of October, closer to Dia de Los Muertos and they decorated absolutely beautifully. They have the traditional marigolds everywhere throughout the restaurant and patio. They even had an ofrenda. I recommend just go here and bundle up to enjoy the delicious food and experience on their patio.  During the restriction in place, they do have outside dining (with walls) and they opened an area of their restaurant that has high-top seating. The top is slightly uncovered, so it can get cold, BUT they do have a few heaters. All staff did have on mask and they require you to wear one, when a server or employee stops by the table. They do check your temperature at the hostess’s stand. Also, hand sanitizer was available. Once you are seated, the table has a QR code sticker to view the menu.  Tzuco is a upscale Mexican cuisine restaurant with a French twist! The menu offers traditional dishes from appetizers to dessert, even wines and cocktails. Every dish has so much detail to it and so much flavor. Even the food presentation has so much detail. Chef Carlos Gaytán is a true artist. Staff was friendly from the moment we walked in and our waiter Keevan made my friends birthday even more special. Keevan was friendly and provided great recommendations.  Every dish was memorable and had so much flavor, that I don’t even have a favorite. For appetizers, we tried:  Mejillones - which is mussels, saffron beurre blanc, dried chorizo, pickled jalapeños served with a baguette. This dish was so good that we even asked for extra bread to dip into the saffron beurre blanc. This was my first time trying dried chorizo and it was sooo good! Honestly, not to sound crazy, but I would have the saffron beurre blanc with a spoon.  Pulpo enamorado - this was a guajillo roasted octopus, with salsa macha, pickled carrot, peas, and potato in Tonnato aioli. This was a little spicy, not bad for me, however, my spice tolerance is high. The pickled carrot, peas and potato was interesting and added a nice crunch with the octopus.  I could have ate the portions for the appetizers alone, so I recommend if you are going to share with someone, try more than one appetizer.  For entrees, my friend and I split this as well, but the portions are good for 1. We tried:  Tzuco burger - I know why order a burger at a upscale Mexican French cuisine restaurant right? IT IS SO WORTH IT and I HIGHLY recommend it. The burger is a beef sirloin, with roasted tomatoes, gruyere cheeese, pickled YELLOW BEETS, black truffle sauce, and black truffle aioli, served with pommes fries. Again, soooo much flavor! I purposely capitalized the YELLOW BEETS, because you read that right. I have NEVER tried yellow beets, nor have I ever had beets on my burger, and this was sooo good! Every ingredient was tasty and the burger was cooked perfectly. I drenched the burger in the black aioli sauce and mmmmm it was so good! I even dipped my fries into the aioli! The fries are garlic butter and Parmesan cheese and again cooked perfectly, with a nice crunch.  Pesca Deli Dia - this is fish of the day in some mole verde sauce, had pickled red onions and then it is served with tamal Nejo which is like flat unstuffed tamales. If you never heard, had or seen this, it’s kinda like a cold potato. This dish was very good and the portion was definitely enough to share.  To end our meal, they brought my friend a complimentary dessert.

Upscale Mexican restaurant with absolutely delicious food and great ambience. My girlfriend and I tried the ceviche tatemado, corn esquites, daily spread, and pulpo enamorado - all were phenomenal and beautifully presented, though our personal favorite was the octopus. My only gripe is that service was fairly slow, as it took over 30 minutes between our first and second round of food. Despite this, I'd love to return!  Note: I want to add this just as a quick heads up to the management - when we asked for the check, the waiter placed it in front of me rather than between me and my girlfriend. I know it's small, but it's something that waiters should know not to assume since it promotes some patriarchal ideas about who the "bread winner" is.  Edit: recently returned, and the second meal was even better than the first. The maiz y azafran was one of the best desserts I've had in Chicago. The ceviche verde was delicious and very playful with both texture and temperature. The pescadilla was the only item that did not impress.

I am not a fan of giving negative reviews but the way my boyfriend and I were treated this weekend was unacceptable for an upscale restaurant. While I wouldn’t consider us one of the regulars, this wasn’t our first or second time dining at Tzuco.  Over the weekend, on a Saturday around 8/9pm, my boyfriend and I wanted to grab a drink and some apps. We go up to the hostesses outside and ask if we can come in for a drink. What looked like the manager, skimmed her iPad and dismissed us rudely by saying “we are busy at the moment.” She did not try to accommodate us and didn’t ask if we wanted to put our name down to make a reservation for the next available table. This made me wonder if the staff treated us the way they did because of the way we were dressed casually or because of our American flag face mask?  We walk away a few steps and out of curiosity, I pull up the online reservations just to see that the next available time slot was within a 20 min wait... so we book a reservation for 9:15pm. We get seated on the patio, and had to wait 20+ min for someone to come and greet us. At this point we lost our appetite, and wanted to leave. However, after what we had to go through, we decided to order two drinks for which we had to wait another 15 min. A simple mimosa and a cocktail.  We get our drinks, and another 15 min passes before the waitress comes to our table to ask if we want to order anything. (Just wanted to mention how she was frequently checking up on the tables around us). Anyways, we ask for the check which was brought to us immediately. We else could go wrong? The waitress failed to give us a pen and was no where to be found. At this point we just want to leave. We were forced to sign the bill with a LIP LINER.  The two stars are for good food and drinks.

When the check came our food did not reappear. Turns out that the restaurant threw  the food away.  The food and the service was pretty good but they did throw away about $100 worth of food. The food was delicious!!!! I'm leaving only 4 stars because the service needs some serious improvement :(. We had the camarón & sandía and it was so fresh and well seasoned. The mejillones were succulent and the beurre blanc was so tasty. The esquites were nice and smokey. For entrees we had the Chile relleno and pork pibil. The Chile relleno was nicely seasoned, the filling was full of flavor and had a a good amount of umami. The pibil was nice and tender and the beans and salsa had the perfect balance of saltyness, acid and heat. For desserts we had the pingüino and the avocado dessert. They were tasty but the pingüino was missing something fruity (perhaps a raspberry coulis or jam?). Also the pearls in the avocado dessert were super limey (sour), in my opinion they needed to be diluted a little or maybe needed a little more sugar. My only reccomendation is that servers/food runner need some re-training. The camarón & sandia needs to be served with teaspoons for everybody at the table just so we can enjoy the delicious aguachile. The mejillones bread should be pre-sliced (or at least scored). The bread is so hard to cut with the butter knife provided. And only 4 tortillas for the pibil? We had about ten tacos out of the plate and the first round of tortillas were cold. I went ahead and spoke with the server about these concerns and, unfortunately, his response could have been better. He proceeded to blame the food runners for the mistakes and wasn't able to fix the problem right away (literally just say: "I'm sorry" and bring more spoons, that's it) Chef Gaytan, your menu is amazing! I can't wait to come back and eat your delicious food again.

If you're looking for outstanding and wonderful food and service, this is the place..Chef Carlos Gaytan and his team do an amazing job, and took TZUCO to a whole new level! This is a 5 star Experience!!

A surprise dinner date! Thought my husband would appreciate the authenticity of Tzuco. We were more than pleased for our first visit. Service was good, food was excellent!  The overall design had a true mexico feel. We will for sure be back!
Best short rib ever! Incredible deserts

Welcome home to Chicago Carlos!  The food is truly delicious. The French Onion Soup was smooth with a great texture.  The pork shank and short ribs had a wonderful depth of flavor and made great tacos with the warm flour tortillas. We ate several starters, one with watermelon that was awesome.  The unique mixture of French and Mexican cuisine are truly ingenious. The service was great!  Warm, friendly, well informed staffers made our dining experience one we will definitely repeat and recommend. Oh and my lemon drop martini was perfectly balanced.  Chicago missed Mexique but Tzuco is a foodie paradise!

Exceptional dining experience; the staff were amazingly hospitable, the food was incredible with very earthy and unique flavours and the mixologist blew our minds with his creative cocktails. Dinner at Tzuco was a real treat

My daughter and I recently had the opertunity to eat here. In fact it was before they officially opened and during their very first service in which patrons were being served. The whole resturant was abuzz with people trying to learn their roles and identify specific functions. You could tell that a lot of work went into the training and now it was time to polish. After we were seated, we were welcomed by a greeter by the name of Linda. She proceeded to educate us about the history of Tzuco and how it came about. Everything from the authentic decor right down to the precise ingredients in the food has been carefully selected and imorted to become an intrical piece of this dining experience. We shared several selections from the varied menu and there was not a single item that we could brag more about. Everything was crafted with care and precision. Linda met with us several time during the course of our meal. She was very knowledgable, friendly and welcoming. We will definitly be going back soon and taking more friends and family. .

Started with ‘breads and spreads’ which set the tone for how much love and care go into every dish. We enjoyed everything we had and will undoubtedly return to try the rest. Excellent experience overall.

Amazing place, unique decorations, modern but keept authenticity. Service is great!, Food is to die for! Fell in love with their food. Loved the pila with faucets right outside of the bathrooms, there is a heart touch story about it... Thank you for having us at your family and friends event. Will be back soon for sure!

There are few meals I can say have completely surprised and delighted me to the extent that the meal at Tzuco did. The decor helps to teleport you down to Mexico.  The staff are extremely attentive and helpful.  Tzuco is another homerun for Chef Carlos.

So much unique thinking and undeniable effort reward we their guests with a vacation away from our normal.  The food is perfect.  The service is genuinely attentive.  The Jericalla dessert is nothing short of outstanding.
